First digital painting
I'm back and trying to learn some digital painting!

images.description: The amazing support from my last post inspired me to keep going and try new things! I started trying to wrap my head around digital painting techniques! Something which I've wanted to do for a very long time, but seemed impossible.

I started by watching a video on a colour temperature study by the amazing moderndayjames on Youtube! His video was amazing to slow down and watch the techniques of painting, from sketch to values and colouring, and finally creating hard lines! (All of which I knew I'd need to practice)!

Practiced on this awesome T-rex skull!

Check out the video if you're interested! https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=w04rmaqYzfs&t=566s

I loved the process of painting, so shortly after Christmas, I dove back in and worked on a metal armour study of Oscar of Astora's helmet from Darksouls! I found the process of figuring out where to put the hard edges quite difficult, but stuck with it!

data.title: Look at this big ol' chunk of clay I found and painted !

images.description:
I work on a college campus in the Fine Arts department as a janitor, so I often come across art that has been tossed for being "imperfect" or simply because the artist did not want it. I do not sell what I find or what I create out of what I've found, I just like making things and I love art. 

I found this freaking sweet chunk of clay that dried out so I painted it with acrylic using burnt umber, red, yellow ocre, orange, and black. I used an artist sponge at first to apply the first base layer of color, then I used a carpenter's brush after the sponge wore out, theeennn I noticed the brush was shedding so I ended up finger painting the rest (mainly the red center) and I loved how it turned out.

I picked cattails because I've always liked them.

Oh lawd, at first I freaking thought I should "seal" the clay before painting on it in case it absorbed too much color or something (I ain't no scientist but I thought), so I coated it with what I thought was a sealer... Turns out it was a sealer for WOOD. I spent about a good hour painting before it all bubbled up and popped. 

Thankfully I could just peel it off and start over.

This is how I painted it after I had to peel it all off.

I wish I could duplicate this because it looked so fucking beautiful just on its own with the color and the raw looking edges. 

But hey, ain't nothing wrong with cattails.
